<TITLE> Tigers lose first ODI </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 5 (bdnews24.com) -- Bangladesh lost the first one-day international against New Zealand by 146 runs at McLean Park in Napier on Friday. Chasing an improbable 337-run target, the Tigers lost their way after top-scorer Tamim Iqbal and Imrul Kayes put on a half-century stand to be eventually bowled out for 190 in 43.5 overs. Tamim (62 off 69 balls) and Kayes (29-ball 33) added 71 runs in 11 overs. But it went to waste after Bangladesh's top-order failed to get into double figures. Kiwi skipper Daniel Vettori rocked the boat claiming 3-33. Jacob Oram, Andy McKay and Martin Guptill weighed in with two wickets each. Daryl Tuffey took one wicket. Earlier, a whirlwind half-century from man of the match Oram helped the Black Caps pile up an imposing 336-9 in 50 overs. The all-rounder smashed 83 off just 40 deliveries to revive the innings after the hosts, who won the toss, were at one stage on the ropes at 187-6 after 36 overs. But a magnificent 123-run stand between Oram and Neil Broom (71 off 73 balls) snatched the initiative. Besides, opener Peter Ingram made a 74-ball 69 and Ross Taylor scored 51 off 52 deliveries. Shafiul Islam captured 4-68 while Shahadat Hossain, Shakib Al Hasan and Naeem Islam took one wicket each. The second one-dayer will be played in Dunedin on F
